  "text": "The Android Activity lifecycle is implemented across four key components in the AOSP framework:\n\n1. **Activity.java** (core/java/android/app/Activity.java, line 763)\n   - The base Activity class that defines the lifecycle callback methods: onCreate(), onStart(), onResume(), onPause(), onStop(), and onDestroy()\n   - These protected methods are overridden by application developers to respond to lifecycle events\n\n2. **ActivityThread.java** (core/java/android/app/ActivityThread.java, line 296)\n   - The main thread of an Android application that handles lifecycle transitions on the client side\n   - Contains key handler methods: handleLaunchActivity() (line 4286), handleResumeActivity() (line 5414), handleStopActivity() (line 5835), and handleDestroyActivity() (line 6074)\n   - Processes messages from the system server and executes corresponding lifecycle callbacks\n\n3. **ActivityRecord.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityRecord.java, line 410)\n   - The server-side representation of an Activity in the Window Manager service\n   - Tracks the state and properties of activities running on the system\n   - Manages visibility, focus, and other activity-specific attributes\n\n4. **ActivityTaskManagerService.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityTaskManagerService.java, line 324)\n   - The system service responsible for managing activity stacks and tasks\n   - Orchestrates lifecycle transitions across the entire system\n   - Coordinates activity launching, pausing, resuming, and stopping across applications\n\nThese components work together: ActivityTaskManagerService makes decisions about what activities should transition to what state, communicates with ActivityThread through ClientTransactions, and ActivityThread executes those transitions by calling the appropriate lifecycle methods on the Activity instance."
